00:11:57.140 --> 00:12:00.260
So basically this is a weather dataset.

00:12:00.260 --> 00:12:02.539
And what I've done is I used some colorless code.

00:12:02.539 --> 00:12:03.539
Probably pretty poorly.

00:12:03.539 --> 00:12:05.539
But I did my best.

00:12:05.539 --> 00:12:08.619
And what I've done is I made list columns with temperature and humidity.

00:12:08.619 --> 00:12:11.940
Because the idea there is I want to show a lot of, like, basically all the temperature

00:12:11.940 --> 00:12:12.940
data per day.

00:12:12.940 --> 00:12:14.820
So I've got an aggregate of every day.

00:12:14.820 --> 00:12:15.820
There's some temperature data.

00:12:15.820 --> 00:12:16.820
There's some humidity data.

00:12:16.820 --> 00:12:20.659
And we're gonna make a table out of this.

00:12:20.659 --> 00:12:21.659
Okay.

00:12:21.659 --> 00:12:22.659
So this looks bad.

00:12:22.659 --> 00:12:23.659
But it's gonna get better.

00:12:23.659 --> 00:12:24.659
Trust me.

00:12:24.659 --> 00:12:26.460
So I added a header with a title and a subtitle this time.

00:12:26.460 --> 00:12:30.780
And you might see that, you know, like, the list columns, they look fully printed out.

00:12:30.780 --> 00:12:32.900
It's gonna look better.

00:12:32.900 --> 00:12:37.140
Because what I'm doing is I'm gonna use a method called format nanoplot.

00:12:37.140 --> 00:12:40.140
And what it does is it actually makes little plots inside of your table.

00:12:40.140 --> 00:12:44.219
And these are, like, really nice fun plots that you can customize.

00:12:44.219 --> 00:12:46.739
And they pack a lot of data into a table.

00:12:46.739 --> 00:12:49.900
And they fit nicely inside the table cells.

00:12:49.900 --> 00:12:50.900
They're very customizable.

00:12:51.140 --> 00:12:55.460
So what we've done here is we've used the nanoplot options helper and sort of saved

00:12:55.460 --> 00:12:56.460
that to nanoops.

00:12:56.460 --> 00:12:58.460
That's what you see on the right.

00:12:58.460 --> 00:13:01.299
It just means that we can customize these individually.

00:13:01.299 --> 00:13:03.020
Okay.

00:13:03.020 --> 00:13:06.460
And then one final thing I'm gonna do for formatting is format the dates so they look

00:13:06.460 --> 00:13:07.460
kind of nice.

00:13:07.460 --> 00:13:09.900
I'm using a format date to do that.

00:13:09.900 --> 00:13:15.260
And it has a bunch of, like, keywords where you can just really simply from some presets

00:13:15.260 --> 00:13:16.260
format the date.

00:13:16.260 --> 00:13:17.260
No must, no fuss.

00:13:17.260 --> 00:13:18.260
That sort of thing.

00:13:18.260 --> 00:13:19.260
Calls label.

00:13:19.979 --> 00:13:23.580
We're doing a cool thing where we actually make it so you get degrees Celsius there with

00:13:23.580 --> 00:13:25.219
a little bit of curly brace code.

00:13:25.219 --> 00:13:28.219
Because you can get symbols from that.

00:13:28.219 --> 00:13:31.059
Otherwise it's a little bit hard to do.

00:13:31.059 --> 00:13:32.059
And there's our table.

00:13:32.059 --> 00:13:34.299
So a lot of data in a table.

00:13:34.299 --> 00:13:36.900
And it's a really great summary of weather.

00:13:36.900 --> 00:13:37.900
Okay.

00:13:37.900 --> 00:13:41.099
Third and final segue about a method.

00:13:41.099 --> 00:13:43.500
This one's format nanoplot.

00:13:43.500 --> 00:13:45.859
Nanoplots were actually inspired by Sparklines, which you may have heard of.

00:13:45.859 --> 00:13:48.979
They were popularized by Tufte in his writings.

00:13:49.700 --> 00:13:52.700
And there's an implementation, of course, in Excel.

00:13:52.700 --> 00:13:54.500
And people really love that feature a lot.

00:13:54.500 --> 00:13:59.539
And so it seemed like a cool thing to do to add to grade tables.

00:13:59.539 --> 00:14:00.539
So here's another table.

00:14:00.539 --> 00:14:02.979
Using a dataset that's actually in grade tables.

00:14:02.979 --> 00:14:05.219
And basically has nanoplots in it.

00:14:05.219 --> 00:14:08.820
And the cool thing about nanoplots is that you can see right away for this patient, the

00:14:08.820 --> 00:14:11.659
white blood cell count increased beyond the normal range.

00:14:11.659 --> 00:14:12.659
And that's super important.

00:14:12.659 --> 00:14:17.919
If you just had numbers, the time to that insight would probably be a little bit lower.

00:14:17.919 --> 00:14:20.400
So this is really good to have.

00:14:20.400 --> 00:14:21.400
And it's also really cool.

00:14:21.400 --> 00:14:24.719
Because you can actually interactively inspect exact values.

00:14:24.719 --> 00:14:29.200
So features of tables, like having precise format values, are there inside nanoplots.

00:14:29.200 --> 00:14:31.280
You just have to hover over the values.

00:14:31.280 --> 00:14:32.799
So that's really super, super cool.

00:14:32.799 --> 00:14:34.799
And actually kind of fun.

00:14:34.799 --> 00:14:36.640
And did I mention that these are all super customizable?

00:14:36.640 --> 00:14:37.919
You can have bars.

00:14:37.919 --> 00:14:39.760
You can have just lines like this.

00:14:39.760 --> 00:14:42.919
It's really quite nice.

00:14:42.919 --> 00:14:44.960
Okay.

00:14:45.000 --> 00:14:48.960
And nanoplots, of course, you can probably think of a million ways to use them.

00:14:48.960 --> 00:14:50.400
Here's just three more examples.

00:14:50.400 --> 00:14:51.400
