00:14:54.640 --> 00:14:58.200
And some sales data based on pizza sales.

00:14:58.200 --> 00:15:00.159
Okay.

00:15:00.159 --> 00:15:05.520
Summing up, you can make really nice, beautiful, I'd say, publication quality tables with grade

00:15:05.520 --> 00:15:06.559
tables.

00:15:06.559 --> 00:15:09.359
I think tables are cool.

00:15:09.359 --> 00:15:11.960
I really feel like they're gonna get their day one day.

00:15:11.960 --> 00:15:13.799
And I know that people love good looking ones.

00:15:14.359 --> 00:15:19.159
When I see a table with data I care about, I'll pore over that table for quite a while.

00:15:19.159 --> 00:15:20.159
It's really amazing.

00:15:20.159 --> 00:15:25.479
And you don't have to compromise on reproducibility when you use grade tables.

00:15:25.479 --> 00:15:28.080
You can basically use grade tables in the visualization step.

00:15:28.080 --> 00:15:29.760
You don't have to dump out your data.

00:15:29.760 --> 00:15:32.440
You can just use it all in one go.

00:15:32.440 --> 00:15:38.960
And your reports and such will probably be greatly improved because of that.

00:15:38.960 --> 00:15:41.239
So to get started with grade tables, it's on PyPI.

00:15:41.239 --> 00:15:43.760
So you can just pip install grade tables.

00:15:43.760 --> 00:15:46.840
And there's a great project website we have at PositDev.

00:15:46.840 --> 00:15:49.359
I'm from Posit, by the way.

